    cellular: { title: "Post-Renal Obstructive AKI", content: "Post-renal AKI results from obstruction of urinary outflow at any level from the renal pelvis to the urethra. For obstruction to cause AKI, it must be bilateral (affecting both kidneys) or affect a solitary functioning kidney, unless the obstruction is at the bladder outlet or urethra (which affects both kidneys simultaneously). Common causes include benign prostatic hyperplasia (BPH) in older men, kidney stones (bilateral or in a solitary kidney), tumors compressing the ureters, neurogenic bladder, and blood clots. At the cellular level, the increased hydrostatic pressure from urinary backflow transmits retrograde through the collecting system to the nephrons, eventually exceeding the filtration pressure in Bowman's capsule and halting glomerular filtration. Prolonged obstruction leads to hydronephrosis and eventually permanent tubular atrophy and interstitial fibrosis if not relieved." },
