    cellular: { title: "CKD Classification and GFR Decline", content: "CKD is classified into 5 stages based on GFR and albuminuria. Stage 1 (GFR ≥90) has kidney damage with normal or increased GFR - often detected only by albuminuria or structural abnormalities. Stage 2 (GFR 60-89) represents mild GFR reduction. Stage 3 is subdivided into 3a (GFR 45-59) and 3b (GFR 30-44), representing moderate decline where complications begin appearing. Stage 4 (GFR 15-29) is severe reduction with prominent uremic symptoms and preparation for renal replacement therapy. Stage 5 (GFR <15) is kidney failure (ESRD) requiring dialysis or transplantation. The KDIGO classification also incorporates albuminuria categories: A1 (<30 mg/g, normal), A2 (30-300 mg/g, moderately increased), and A3 (>300 mg/g, severely increased). Higher albuminuria at any GFR stage indicates worse prognosis. Complications progressively worsen: anemia appears at Stage 3, secondary hyperparathyroidism at Stage 3-4, metabolic acidosis at Stage 4, and uremic syndrome at Stage 4-5." },
